data.content:
Your test works but `Assert.IsTrue` gives unhelpful failure messages (just "Expected: True, Actual: False"). Use MSTest's specialized collection assertions instead:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Shows "collection was empty" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Shows "Expected count: 3, Actual: 2" |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(...)` | Clearer null failure message |

For the "all users are active" check, `Assert.IsTrue` with a LINQ predicate is acceptable since there's no built-in "assert all match" API. You could alternatively loop:

```csharp
foreach (var user in users)
{
    Assert.IsTrue(user.IsActive, $"User {user.Name} was not active");
}
```

This gives you a per-item failure message identifying *which* user failed.
